  283323.1 * 10^6 # total value of dwellings owned by non-households

pc.prop_val_due_NG <- 
  paste0(round(100*present.value_benefit_from_NG / total.value.of.property.2014), "\\%")
pc.prop_val_due_NG_Quaran <-
  paste0(round(100*present.value_benefit_from_Quaran_NG / total.value.of.property.2014), "\\%")
@

The impact on prices depends on investor perceptions of the size of the lost tax benefit. 
Average annual rental losses over the last decade were \$\Sexpr{texNum(mean(rental_losses$real_tot_avg_loss))}, generating annual tax write-offs worth an average of \$\Sexpr{texNum(mean(value.of.ng.by.yr$total_benefit_real))} in today's dollars. 
If investor expectations are guided by history, the present value of tax benefits over the next decade from negative gearing is around \$\Sexpr{texNum(present.value_benefit_from_NG)}. The present value of tax benefits in perpertuity is \$\Sexpr{texNum(mean(value.of.ng.by.yr$total_benefit_real)/RoR_proprty)}.

If negative gearing were entirely abolished, then these expected tax benefits would be lost entirely. 
Given that the value of dwellings held by investors is \$\Sexpr{texNum(total.value.of.property.2014)} (2014), a loss of \$\Sexpr{texNum(present.value_benefit_from_NG)} from the value would correspond to a fall in prices of \Sexpr{pc.prop_val_due_NG}. 
For policies that limit negative gearing the price impacts would be smaller since some of the tax benefits are retained. 
For example, if investment losses are quarantined so they can't be written off against wage and salary income, the present value of tax benefits lost over a decade might be \$\Sexpr{round(present.value_benefit_from_Quaran_NG/1e9)}~billion, with a maximum impact on property prices of \Sexpr{pc.prop_val_due_NG_Quaran}.

Alternatively, assuming that investors demand the same return on investment without negative gearing, the change could be as high as \Sexpr{latex_percent(change_in_price_due_to_NG_upper)}. This is equal to the proportion of the current value of investor residential property in the value of negative gearing as a perpetuity. (The post-tax return on residential property investment was \Sexpr{latex_percent(RoR_proprty)} in the decade to December 2013.)

Let $V_0$ be the current value of (investor, residential) housing stock. Let $V_{10}$ be the value of $V_0$ in ten years' time. Let $V_{0\not{G}}'$ be the new value of housing stock in the absence of negative gearing. Let $G$ be the value of negative gearing in perpertuity. Let $r$ be the rate of return demanded in residential property. So 
\[V_{10} = V_0(1 + r)^{10}\]
and by assumption
\begin{align*}
V_{10} - G &= V_{0\not{G}}' (1 + r)^{10} \\
V_{0\not{G}}' &= \frac{V_{10} - G}{(1 + r)^{10}} \\
              &= \frac{V_0(1 +r)^{10} - G}{(1 + r)^{10}} \\
\implies \frac{V_{0\not G}'}{V_0} &= 1 - \frac{G}{V_0(1 + r)^{10}}
\end{align*}

Thus \[\frac{V_{0\not G}'}{V_0} = \text{\Sexpr{latex_percent(1 - value_of_NG_perpertuity * NG_inflator(1)/(total.value.of.property.2014 * (1 + RoR_proprty)^(1)))}}.\]
\end{bigbox*}

One concern with limiting negative gearing is that downward pressure on house prices could leave some highly geared investors with negative equity.  
But given expected one-off price impacts of less than 
\Sexpr{pc.prop_val_due_NG} 
(\Vref{box:Impact_of_NG_on_house_prices}), the risk of negative equity from the tax changes is limited. 
Only around ten per cent of new property loans go to investors with loan value ratios in excess of 90 per cent.\footcite{APRA2015}  
And ratios for existing loans are falling as property prices continue to grow. 
For the small proportion of investors that remain highly leveraged, higher interest rates pose a far greater risk than changes to the tax treatment of rental losses.

\subsubsection{Limiting negative gearing will not change rents much}
But out of all the effects that negative gearing has on housing markets, its effect on rental prices is by far the most contentious.

Concerns persist that limiting negative gearing will reduce the supply of rental properties and push up rents.
These arguments typically rest on two pillars: one, that rental prices rose in the 1980s when negative gearing for property was restricted and two, that investors will abandon the market without present tax advantages. 

The first argument is quite easily refuted.
In 1985, the Hawke Government restricted negative gearing so that rental losses could not be used to reduce tax payable on other income streams. 
Two years later, the policy was abolished out of concern for increasing rental prices.

But these concerns were ill-founded. Rents did rise rapidly in Perth and rose somewhat in Sydney. 
Yet inflation-adjusted rents were stable in Melbourne and actually fell in Adelaide and Brisbane (\Vref{fig:Capital_city_rents}).
In Sydney and Perth it was population growth and insufficient residential construction -- due to high borrowing rates and competition from the stock market for funds -- not the policy change, that effected the rent rises.\footcites[p.~186]{badcock1991responsiveness}[pp.~47-48]{Daley2013} 
The policy change was merely a coincidence.
As Badcock and Browett remark in their 1991 post-mortem of the policy, 

\begin{quote}
While it was clearly in the interests of the real estate industry to exaggerate the effects of the tax reforms, the federal government was misguided in its acceptance of the pervasiveness of the `rent crisis' in mid-1987.
\end{quote}

Recent rhapsodies by the property lobby show that little has changed.\footnote{See for example \emph{Analysis of Negative Gearing and CGT discount for residential property} (2015)}  The real estate industry is happy to exaggerate the effect of abolishing negative gearing on rental prices and governments are unenthusiastic to contradict them.\footcite{CormannLateline2015}

